    financialSnapshot: "Sydney 3-bed house in Coogee. Purchased 2015 for $1.1M. Current estimated value $1.85M. Rented since 2021 when Rachel relocated to London for a UK tech role. Rental $900/week. No mortgage remaining.",
    painPoint: "Rachel planned to sell the Sydney home in late 2026 when her son starts senior school. Assumed the main residence exemption would still apply because she lived in the property 2015-2021. A casual conversation with an Australian accountant friend revealed the 9 May 2017 rule — Rachel's expected tax-free sale was actually facing a $750k gain taxed at 45% non-resident rate = ~$337k tax, plus $231k withholding at settlement.",
    discovery: "Rachel googled 'Australian main residence exemption expat' and found the ATO page on the 9 May 2017 rule. Realisation: her residency at the CONTRACT date — not her residency history — was the entire test. Sell as a London-based non-resident = exemption gone.",
    voice: "Analytical, detail-oriented, furious that this rule change didn't make international news when it was introduced. Wants precise numbers and concrete options.",
